{"title_page": "Thoothukudi massacre", "text_new": "{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Thoothukudi police firing|2=Talk:Thoothukudi massacre#Requested move 14 April 2020 }}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Thoothukudi Massacare\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| map         = {{Location map|Tamil Nadu|lat=8.48|long=78.04|caption=}}\n| map_caption = Location of Thoothukudi in Tamil Nadu\n| location    = [[Thoothukudi]], Tamil Nadu, [[India]]\n| target      = Protestors against [[Sterlite Copper]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|8.784117|78.099142|display=inline,title}}\n| date        = 22 May 2018\n| time        = \n| timezone    = UTC +5:30\n| type        = [[Shooting]]<!-- Don't change without valid reference -->\n| fatalities  = 13<!-- Don't change without valid reference --><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india-sterlite-protest-live-updates-tuticorin-thoothukudi-death-toll-vedanta-copper-plant-443641 |title=Anti-Sterlite protests: 15 dead, 102 injured in Thoothukudi; electricity supply to Sterlite Industries cut off}}</ref>\n| injuries    = 102<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india-sterlite-protest-live-updates-tuticorin-thoothukudi-death-toll-vedanta-copper-plant-443641 |title=Anti-Sterlite protests: 13 dead, 102 injured in Thoothukudi; electricity supply to Sterlite Industries cut off}}</ref>\n| perps       = [[Tamil Nadu Police]] & Paramilitary forces\n| weapons     = [[L1A1 SLR]] [[battle rifle]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikatan.com/news/tamilnadu/125778-this-is-the-type-of-rifle-used-in-tuticorin.html |title=\u0ba4\u0bc2\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd 11 \u0baa\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b89\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8 \u0b95\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0ba4\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf \u0b87\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0bcd}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/massacre-thoothukudi-intelligence-failure-or-deliberate-assault-81865 |title=The police firing in Thoothukudi: Intelligence failure or deliberate assault?}}</ref>\n| numparts    =\n}}\n[[File:Sterlitejpg.jpg|thumb|Protesters in large numbers take out a march against the Sterlite copper plant on May 22, 2018.]]\n\nThe '''Thoothukudi Massacre''' (also known as the '''Thoothukudi police firing''' or '''Sterlite protest firing''') is used to denote the events that took place on 22, and 23 May 2018 in [[Thoothukudi]] town of [[Tamilnadu]]. It took place during an ongoing protest against proposed expansion of copper smelter plant run by Sterlite Corporation in Thoothukudi town, ended in death of 13 persons and injuries to many, including police personnel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-44207343}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/victims-with-bleeding-injuries-and-gunshot-wounds-at-thoothukudi-gh/article23962412.ece}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-4-dead-in-police-firing-during-anti-sterlite-protest-in-tamil-nadu-s-thoothukudi-2617688}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/several-anti-sterlite-protesters-policemen-injured-in-thoothukudi/article23957774.ece}}</ref> On 22 May morning, the 100th day Anti Sterlite Protests, thousands of people marched towards the Thoothukudi Collectorate, against legal prohibitory orders passed by the district administration.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/jul/16/anti-sterlite-protests-imposition-of-sec-144-was-not-known-to-public-in-thoothukudi-reveals-report-1843883.html}}</ref> The agitated protestors overpowered police, started pelting stones and torched vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/anti-sterlite-stir-13-dead-public-property-worth-rs-10-2-million-damaged-118052500138_1.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://in.reuters.com/article/vedanta-smelter-insight/no-warning-witnesses-describe-how-police-shot-and-killed-smelter-protesters-in-thoothukudi-idINKCN1IU1W9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/victims-with-bleeding-injuries-and-gunshot-wounds-at-thoothukudi-gh/article23962412.ece}}</ref> Police opened fire killing 12 persons on 22 May, at various places in Thoothukudi Town and as the protest continued, one more person was shot dead on 23rd May.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/anti-sterlite-stir-13-dead-public-property-worth-rs-10-2-million-damaged-118052500138_1.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/one-more-dies-in-police-firing-as-tuticorin-burns-for-the-second-day-death-toll-rises-to-12-1757769.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/one-more-killed-in-fresh-firing-in-thoothukudi/article23967970.ece}}</ref> In a related incident, a women was killed when miscreants, during anti sterlite protests torched a bus on 25 May at [[Srivaikuntam]]  taking the total death toll to 14 in violent incidents related to Anti Sterlite Protests in the district.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/madurai/bus-torching-case-injured-woman-dies-in-hospital/articleshow/64421319.cms}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/arrest-anti-sterlite-protesters-who-set-bus-on-fire-thoothukudi/article24080888.ece}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nSterlite Copper has been facing resistance from the local fishermen\u2019s groups in the area ever since the plant was given permission to be established by the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board in 1994.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sudhakar|first=P.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/for-sterlite-its-crisis-situation-once-again/article4564893.ece|title=For Sterlite, it's crisis situation once again|date=2013-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Sporadic protests have occurred in [[Thoothukudi]] since 1999, directed against the Sterlite Copper smelting works, the factory owned by [[Vedanta Limited]], a subsidiary of [[Vedanta Resources]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/variety/sterlite-protests-sulphur-dioxide-vedanta-tamil-nadu/story/1/23101.html|title=Why hundreds of Tamils won't quit protests against Vedanta's Sterlite|website=www.dailyo.in|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> Protesters opposed the soil, water and air contamination caused by the factory.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/sterlite-s-pollution-problem-113041801267_1.html|title=Sterlite's pollution problem|date=2013-04-18|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Pollution studies ===\nAn epidemiological study carried out by [[Tirunelveli Medical College]] in 2006\u201307 found an increased prevalence of respiratory diseases and ear, nose and throat (ENT) morbidity in the 5-km radius of Sterlite Industries. The study reported the prevalence of respiratory diseases in the area at 13.9% which was far higher than the state average. The prevalence of asthmatic bronchitis is 2.8%, which more than two-times the state average of 1.29%. Myalgia (general body pain) is another extensively reported symptom and women were often found to have menstrual disorders, like [[Menorrhagia|menorrhagiae]] and dysmenorrhagiae in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-how-copper-plant-impacts-health-thoothukudi-people-78772|title=Sterlite - here's the proof: How the copper plant impacts health of Thoothukudi people|last=Jayaraman|first=Nityanand|date=April 1, 2018|website=thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Their report blamed it on the air pollution caused by the industry's thermal power plants and automobiles in the area.<ref>{{cite book | last = Elango  | first = S. | title = Health status and Epidemiological study around 5&nbsp;km radius of Sterlite Industries (India) Limited, Thoothukudi | publisher = Tirunelveli Medical College | date = Oct 2008 | location = Tirunelveli | pages = 106 | language = English | url = https://poromboke.files.wordpress.com/2018/03/health-report-sterlite_edited.pdf}}</ref> The [[groundwater]] iron content in the area of the plant has been found to be 17\u201320 times the allowable limit, causing additional health problems for the population already experiencing higher than average incidence of respiratory diseases. During the time of this Study at 2007, Sterlite was operating at about 18 to 42 percent, compared to its 4 Lakh Tonnes per Annum in the year 2017-2018.<ref name=\"newsminute\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-how-copper-plant-impacts-health-thoothukudi-people-78772|title=Sterlite \u2013 here's the proof: How the copper plant impacts health of Thoothukudi people|date=2018-04-01|work=The News Minute|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/jul/29/sterlite-keen-to-expand-operation-in-thoothukudi-1850064.html|title=Sterlite keen to expand operation in Thoothukudi|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> \n\nThe 1998 report by [[National Environmental Engineering Research Institute]] (NEERI), the levels of selenium, arsenic and lead in treated effluent were higher than specified standards. The team also found dead birds after they consumed the water mixed with the effluent and also reported that the industry's process of cooling the effluents can cause health hazards to the staff and residents in the local region. In another instance, the NEERI reported water samples from dugwells and borewells around the spot were found to be non-[[Drinking water|drinkable]] due to its high chemical content. During 1998, the industry was operating at 10% capacity, compared to that of 2018.  <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-data-how-smelter-likely-cause-water-pollution-79055|title=Sterlite \u2013 here's proof: The data on how the smelter is likely cause for water pollution|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/news/environment/neeri-made-way-for-sterlite-to-pollute-tuticorin-60647|title=NEERI made way for Sterlite to pollute Tuticorin|last=|first=|date=|website=downtoearth.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2005 environmental audit by NEERI, the samples from a village 2-km northwest of the factory had levels of cadmium, copper, lead, chromium, and arsenic 2 to 9 times higher than allowed levels. Soil Samples were also analyzed in areas surrounding the plant during the study and [[Arsenic poisoning|arsenic]] levels ranged from 133 mg/kg to 287 mg/kg, where soils containing more than 50 mg/kg of arsenic are supposed to treated as a 'hazardous wastes' under the Indian Law.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn October 2010, Sampling tests by an NGO, Community Environmental Monitoring, found salinity level in an open well to be of 7854 mg/litre while levels exceeding 2000 mg/litre can badly damage the crops. Another water sample from a bore-well had [[sulfate]] levels 10 times higher than the average. A soil sample from the same spot contained 335 g/kg of iron and a ingestion of just 3.5 grams by a child can be a serious case of [[Iron poisoning|Iron Poisoning]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nA Scientific study in 2017, found most of the ground water samples in the area are highly contaminated with heavy metals like arsenic, lead, boron etc. which were higher than the [[World Health Organization]]'s prescribed limit.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Selvam|first=S.|last2=Antony Ravindran|first2=A.|last3=Venkatramanan|first3=S.|last4=Singaraja|first4=C.|date=2017-05-01|title=Assessment of heavy metal and bacterial pollution in coastal aquifers from SIPCOT industrial zones, Gulf of Mannar, South Coast of Tamil Nadu, India|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s13201-015-0301-3|journal=Applied Water Science|language=en|volume=7|issue=2|pages=897\u2013913|doi=10.1007/s13201-015-0301-3|issn=2190-5495}}</ref>\n\nThe Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board (TNPCB) observed that the unit has been releasing poisonous gas in the air. TNPCB identified that the sulphur dioxide levels went off the scale on the night of March 23, 2013. It showed a reading of 2939.55-mg/cubic meter against the decreed limit of 1250 mg/cubic meter.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2018/columnists/sterlite-protests-reach-a-climax.html|title=Sterlite protests reach a climax|last=Pioneer|first=The|website=The Pioneer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2018, the TNPCB accused the Sterlite Copper of causing groundwater pollution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/news/governance/sterlite-typifies-all-that-s-wrong-with-environmental-governance-in-india-60877|title=Sterlite typifies all that's wrong with environmental governance in India|website=www.downtoearth.org.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Gas leaks ===\nOn July 7th 1997, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board told the company to shut down after a sulphur dioxide gas leak which hospitalized more than 90 people.<ref>{{Cite news|last=BSCAL|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/sterlite-told-to-shut-plant-following-gas-leak-197070701041_1.html|title=Sterlite Told To Shut Plant Following Gas Leak|date=1997-07-07|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe Sterlite Copper factory also made headlines in 2013 after a suspected sulphur dioxide gas leak from one of its smelter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sterlite-plant-idINDEE93005C20130401|title=Sterlite ordered to shut large copper smelter over 'gas leak'|date=2013-04-01|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en}}</ref> The plant was blamed for health issues observed in the area related to gas leakage and residents near-by complained of coughing, [[wheezing]], eye iritation, and [[Miscarriage|miscarriages]] following the leak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1287476/sterlite-coppers-20-years-in-thoothukudi-have-been-marked-by-deaths-miscarriages-and-endless-protests/|title=Protests, miscarriages, deaths: Sterlite Copper's 20 years in Thoothukudi|last=Thomas|first=Sushma U. N, Maria|website=Quartz India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Following the alleged gas leak in March 2013, the then chief minister, the late [[J. Jayalalithaa]], ordered its closure. The company appealed to the [[National Green Tribunal Act|National Green Tribunal]], which overturned the government order. The state moved the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] against it, where the petition was still pending. The plant closed on March 27 of 2018, with the company citing a 15-day maintenance process.<ref name=\"financialexpress\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/sterlite-protest-in-tuticorin-9-killed-in-tamil-nadu-top-developments-history-reasons-behind-violence/1177652/|title=Reasons behind Killings|last=|first=|date=|work=The Financial Express|access-date=}}</ref> The Supreme Court ordered the company to pay a 100-crore fine for polluting the water, air and soil around the plant and the factory was temporarily shutdown by the pollution regulator.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sc-slaps-rs-100-cr-penalty-on-sterlite-for-pollution/article4572805.ece|title=SC slaps Rs. 100 cr. penalty on Sterlite for pollution|last=Venkatesan|first=J.|date=2013-04-02|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-05-28|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> About 150 people were arrested in protests against the plant.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn June 2019, the Tamil Nadu government reported that there were 84 incidents of gas leaks at Sterlite Copper in the year 2013 alone, to the [[Madras High Court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/84-gas-leaks-at-sterlite-in-2013-alone-tn-tells-madras-hc/articleshow/69881981.cms|title=84 gas leaks at Sterlite in 2013 alone, Tamil Nadu tells Madras HC {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Jun 21|first=TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=11:52}}</ref>\n\n== Protests ==\nAlthough there were protests were ongoing since the functioning of the plant, according to most reports the protests that lead to incidents of May 22 and May 23 started on February 11 or 12, 2018. On March 24 of thousands of protesters gathered in Thoothukudi town to demand closure of the plant, which was supported by the traders of the town by shutting down the shops. Media reports suggests that this was comparable to the [[2017 pro-jallikattu protests]]  and Thoothukudi protest has shaken the state<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2018/03/26/stir-sterlite-thoothukudi-vedanta-kamal-vivek-support.html|title=Stir against Sterlite plant sees surge in support; Kamal pledges backing|website=The Week|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. The Sterlite management responded by stating that they have got necessary permission for expansion of the plant. Actor turned politician [[Kamal Haasan]] visited visited Kumarareddiapuram village in support of the protest on April 1.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/kamal-haasan-supports-anti-sterlite-protest/article23407062.ece|title=Kamal Haasan supports anti-Sterlite protest|date=2018-04-01|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-22|others=PTI|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Meanwhile the plant was shut for 15 days for taking up maintenance works on March 29.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2018/04/01/kamal-haasan-in-thoothukudi-in-support-of-anti-sterlite-protests.html|title=Kamal Haasan in Thoothukudi in support of anti-Sterlite protests|website=The Week|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The protesters claimed that the company went on to expand despite the rejection by the government.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Radhakrishnan|first=Sruthi|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/the-hindu-explains-sterlite-protests/article23969542.ece|title=The Hindu explains: Sterlite protests|date=2018-05-23|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vikatan.com/social-affairs/environment/120896-after-kumarettiyapuram-pandarampatti-village-people-joins-sterlite-protest-in-thoothukudi|title=\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bc6\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbe\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc8\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b9f\u0bcd \u0b86\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b8e\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0b9f \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bc1 \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bae\u0bcd!|last=|first=|date=|website=vikatan.com|language=ta|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/may/27/anti-sterlite-in-thoothukudi-heart-of-darkness-1819970.html|title=Anti-Sterlite in Thoothukudi: Heart of darkness|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The protests were joined by traders of Thoothukudi city central trade association on the same day following calls for a [[bandh]] by coordinator of the protest M Krishnamoorthi. It is also reported that section of the traders and lorry owners association did not participate in the March 24 protest. According to media reports police sources confirmed the compny's allegation that 'external forces' instigating agitations. One of the company representative D. Dhanavel rubbished the agitation as \u201cfalse propaganda\u201d and said the smelting plant maintained \u201cvery low\u201d emission level. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/200318/thoothukudi-foreign-hand-behind-anti-sterlite-stir.html|title=Thoothukudi: \u2018Foreign hand\u2019 behind anti-Sterlite stir|date=2018-03-20|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> [[Vaiko]] has sought an injunction against the functioning and extension of the copper smelting plant, in the Madurai Bench of High Court of Madras. A division bench of he the Court sought a counter be filed for the existing unit and posted the case for further hearing on June 7. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Reporter|first=Staff|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/puducherry/vaiko-seeks-closure-of-sterlite-copper-plant/article23688489.ece|title=Vaiko seeks closure of Sterlite copper plant|date=2018-04-27|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> \nMeanwhile, Sterlite  moved the Madras High Court for passing prohibitory orders under IPC section 144, as it feared the protest to be organised on May 22 may turn violent. The petitioner alleged that there was a plan to unleash violence and even \"burn down the factory\", and said the regulatory order banning assembly of four or more persons could prevent such incidents.   <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/sterlite-moves-hc-for-addl-security-in-view-of-may-22-protest/1309916 |work=Sterlite petitions High Court}}</ref>\n\nThe District Administration called up 23 people belonging to the trader associations and anti-sterlite activists from the protesters including the environmental activist Fatima Babu on 20th May for a peace meeting. The members agreed to shift the venue after pressure from the government, from the [[district collector|Collector's Office]] to SAV ground and to convert the protest as \u2018attention seeking protest\u2019. Fatima was soon expelled by the protesting group after she agreed to the shift.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/tuticorin-protests-sterlite-industries-illegally-obtained-environmental-clearance-activist-fatima-babu-tells-madras-high-court-4480681.html|title=Tuticorin protests: Sterlite Industries 'illegally obtained' environmental clearance, activist Fatima Babu tells Madras High Court|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nTwo groups of people protested separately on 22nd May. One of them was protesting a attention-seeking protest at SAV ground  and the other was marching towards the Collector's office. Soon both the groups joined together and marched toward the Collector's office. Police resorted to [[lathi charge]] and fired tear gas shells at the crowd after disagreeing with the protesters who wanted to stage a sit-in.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Joseph|first=J. Praveen Paul|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/several-anti-sterlite-protesters-policemen-injured-in-thoothukudi/article23957774.ece|title=10 killed in police firing as anti-Sterlite rally turns violent in Thoothukudi|date=2018-05-22|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> There were about 2000 police personnel and a crowd of over 20,000 protesters. The district administration played down the intelligence reports of mass mobilization of over 18,000 people in the district, assuming that expulsion of Fatima and imposition of Section 144 would de-escalate the protest.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAn employee of the Sterlite Copper claimed the involvement of groups like Makkal Athikaram and Foil Vedanta in the protests.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/880329/view-from-the-other-side-sterlite-workers-attacked-by-thoothukudi-protestors-recall-the-terror|title=View from the other side: Sterlite workers attacked by Thoothukudi protestors recall the terror|last=Govindarajan|first=Vinita|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Firing==\n\nOn May 22, 2018, thousands of people began to march to the District Dollector's office to submit a petition when the \"[[section 144]]\" was imposed. Section 144 makes a gathering of more than four people unlawful but an unofficial release said 20,000 people took out a procession towards the district-collector's office and the copper plant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2018/05/27/sterlite-protest-section-144-lifted-in-thoothukudi.html|title=Sterlite protest: Section 144 lifted in Thoothukudi|website=The Week|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Protestors were successful in entering the premises of the collectorate. The police started shooting against the protesters, \"without any formal warning\" after tear gas and lathi charge proved ineffective.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/anti-sterlite-protests-tuticorin-villagers-accuse-left-outfit-of-inciting-violence-5247129/|title=Anti-Sterlite protests: Tuticorin villagers accuse Left outfit of inciting violence|date=2018-07-06|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/6-km-stir-ended-bloodshed-671436.html|title=A 6-km stir that ended in bloodshed|date=2018-05-23|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\nThe police started shooting at the protesters and were also accused of shooting without any formal warning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/6-km-stir-ended-bloodshed-671436.html|title=A 6-km stir that ended in bloodshed|date=2018-05-23|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref> Police were also reported of intentionally shooting at the heads of the protesters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/police-targeted-protesters-shot-head-victims-families-671547.html|title=Police targeted the protesters; shot at head|date=2018-05-24|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref> 13 protesters were killed including a 17-year old school student, and dozens were injured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/she-wanted-be-lawyer-her-dreams-lie-box-thoothukudi-teen-victim-s-kin-81854|title=She wanted to be a lawyer, her dreams lie in a box|date=2018-05-24|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"fivedays\" /><ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/as-tuticorin-weeps-for-13-felled-in-police-firing-a-quite-rage-persists/articleshow/64334132.cms</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/tamil-nadu/tamil-nadu-police-fired-from-assault-rifles-on-anti-sterlite-protesters-heard-saying-at-least-one-should-die-2110643.html|title=Tamil Nadu Police fired from assault rifles on anti-Sterlite protesters, heard saying at least one should die{{!}} Zee News India|website=zeenews.india.com|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref>\n\n[[First information report|FIR]]<nowiki/>s filed in local police stations, claimed that the order to shoot was issued by officers in the rank of deputy Tehsildars and people pointed out that only collectors have the authority to issue shooting orders.<ref name=\"TH20180529-1\">{{cite news | last = Pon Vasanth | first = B. A | title = Three officers in the rank of deputy tahsildar issued firing orders in Thoothukudi, say FIRs | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Madurai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 29 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/3-deputy-tahsildars-issued-firing-orders-say-firs/article24017934.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Tamil Nadu government ordered a shutdown of Internet in the entire districts of Tuticorin, Tirunelveli and Kanyakumari for five days after the firing.<ref name=\"fivedays\">{{cite web |title=Sterlite protest: Tamil Nadu orders internet suspension for five days in three southern districts |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/may/23/sterlite-protest-tamil-nadu-orders-internet-suspension-for-five-days-in-three-southern-districts-1818574.html |website=New Indian Express |accessdate=9 July 2018 |date=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n==Reactions==\n\n* [[Thirumurugan Gandhi]], the coordinator of [[May 17 Movement]], took the issue to the 38th session of the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]], Geneva in July 2018. On 9 August 2018, Thirumurugan Gandhi was detained by immigration authorities at Bangalore Airport on his return to India and charged under Section 124 A (sedition), 153 A (1) and 153 (b) of IPC for speaking about the Thoothukudi firings at the UNHRC. Court, later, refused to remand him under judicial custody as it found the charges are baseless.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/court-refuses-detain-activist-thirumurugan-gandhi-86351|title=Court refuses to detain activist Thirumurugan Gandhi|date=2018-08-10|work=The News Minute|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/aug/10/thirumurugan-gandhi-held-in-bengaluru-for-un-speech-on-police-firing-in-thoothukudi-1855732.html|title=Thirumurugan Gandhi held in Bengaluru for UN speech on police firing in Thoothukudi|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n* [[Indian National Congress]] party president [[Rahul Gandhi]] described it as \"[[state-sponsored terrorism]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/india/anti-sterlite-protest-gunning-down-9-people-by-police-in-tamil-nadu-is-state-sponsored-terrorism-says-rahul-gandhi-2110523.html?src=fb|title=Anti-Sterlite protest: Gunning down 9 people by police in Tamil Nadu is state-sponsored terrorism, says Rahul Gandhi|date=2018-05-22|work=Zee News|access-date=2018-05-22|language=en}}</ref> \n*[[Seeman (politician)|Seeman]] condemned the firing, and his political party held a rally in Tirunelveli condemning the shooting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tamil.oneindia.com/news/tamilnadu/seeman-condemns-the-gun-firing-at-thoothukudi-protest/articlecontent-pf308746-320470.html|title=Naam Thamizhar Katchi leader Seeman condemns gun firing at Thoothukudi|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref>\n* [[Kamal Haasan]] was one of the first political leaders to arrive to Tuticorin to see the injured in the hospital, after the shootings.\n* [[Vaiko]] and [[M.K.Stalin]] demanded investigations into the shootings.<ref>http://indianexpress.com/article/india/mass-murder-of-innocent-people-dmks-stalin-questions-order-to-fire-at-anti-sterlite-protesters-5187874/</ref>\n* [[National Human Rights Commission of India]] demanded investigation into the killings.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/05/indian-police-accused-killing-11-protesters-180523134721427.html |title=Indian police accused of killing at least 11 protesters}}</ref> It asked its Director General (Investigation) to send a team headed by an [[Superintendent of Police|SP]] to visit the spot and conduct an inquiry.<ref name=\"TH20180530-1\" />\n* Tamils and [[Tamil diaspora]] across the world including [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[Europe]], [[Malaysia]], [[Sri Lanka]] and [[Australia]] held protests against the killing.\n* In support of the protests The UK's Opposition, Labour Party, has called for Vedanta to be delisted from the London Stock Exchange. [[John McDonnell]], the UK's Shadow Chancellor, said removing Vedanta Resources from the London financial markets would prevent reputational damage from the \"rogue\" company which has been operating \"illegal\" mining concerns for years. \"After the firing on the protestors this week, regulators must now take action. Vedanta must be immediately delisted from the London Stock Exchange to remove its cloak of respectability, restore confidence in the governance of the Stock Exchange, and prevent further reputational damage to London's financial markets from this rogue corporation,\" McDonnell said in a statement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uk-opposition-wants-vedanta-delisted-from-london-stock-exchange/articleshow/64331300.cms |title=UK Opposition wants Vedanta delisted on London Stock Exchange}}</ref>\n* Actor [[Rajinikanth]] said \"The entire problem started after anti-social elements attacked police and burned down collector's office, as a result, peaceful protestors were killed. If you undertake protest for each and everything, Tamil Nadu will be turned into a cemetery\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-44313804|title=Rajinikanth: Anger after actor justifies deadly police firing|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/rajinikanth-blames-anti-social-elements-for-sterlite-protest201805302030500001/ |title=Rajinikanth blames anti-social elements for Sterlite protest}}</ref> His reaction to the firing was criticized on the social media.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-superstar-rajinikanth-apologises-for-losing-cool-at-media-interaction-2621031 |title=Superstar Rajinikanth apologises for losing cool at media interaction |access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/rajinikanth-s-speech-earns-him-negative-image-on-social-media-news-tamil-sf5jD6fcigihb.html|title=Rajinikanth's speech earns him negative image on social media?|access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref> Following his controversial statements regarding the Thoothukudi police firing, the Tamil activist groups in [[Norway]] and [[Switzerland]] banned the release of Rajinikanth's film [[Kaala (2018 film)|''Kaala'']] in Norway and Switzerland by the scheduled world wide release date as of 7 June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tamil.news18.com/news/entertainment/after-norway-kaala-ban-in-swiss-too-24491.html|title=\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe \u0baa\u0b9f\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc8 \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0b9f \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u2013 News18 Tamil|website=News18 Tamil|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tamil.samayam.com/tamil-cinema/movie-news/rajinikanth-kaala-movie-banned-in-switzerland-and-norway/articleshow/64428551.cms|title=\u0bb0\u0b9c\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b92\u0bb0\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7, \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe \u0baa\u0b9f\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8 - Samayam Tamil|date=2018-06-02|work=[[Samayam Tamil]]|access-date=2018-06-03|language=ta}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/foreign-nations-ban-rajinis-kaala-tamil-news-214931|title=Foreign nations ban Rajini's 'Kaala'? - Tamil Movie News \u2013 IndiaGlitz.com|work=IndiaGlitz.com|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> The Tamil diaspora groups in Norway and Switzerland announced that they would not release the films of actors in the future who deliberately hurt the feelings and attitudes of Tamil people following the comments from Rajinikanth on Tamils.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tamilnews.com/2018/06/01/switzerland-ban-super-star-movie-following-norway/|title=\u0ba8\u0bcb\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0baf\u0bc8 \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd '\u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe' \u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8??|last=S|first=Ashwiniya|date=2018-06-01|work=TAMIL NEWS|access-date=2018-06-03|language=en-US}}</ref> However, the ban was later lifted and the film was released within a week, a day before the scheduled worldwide release in Switzerland and Norway.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.topkino.ch/pdf/Programm24.pdf|title=Wochenprogramm|date=2018-06-11|work=Top Kino|access-date=2018-06-19|language=de-CH|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619085834/http://www.topkino.ch/pdf/Programm24.pdf|archivedate=2018-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.filmweb.no/film/article1361077.ece|title=Kaala (Tamil)|date=2018-06-01|work=Filmweb|access-date=2018-06-19|language=no-NO|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619090401/https://www.filmweb.no/film/article1361077.ece|archivedate=2018-06-19}}</ref>The actor was also summoned to appear before the one man commission probing the incident on 25th February. However, the actor cited professional engagements and disturbance caused to the public if a star of his stature arrives at the court to decline appearing before the commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/thoothukudi-sterlite-copper-plant-probe-rajinikanth-gets-exemption-from-appearance-808094.html|title=Thoothukudi Sterlite Copper plant probe: Rajinikanth gets exemption from appearance|date=2020-02-25|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nOn 28 May 2018, the Sterlite factory was sealed after an order given by the Tamil Nadu Environmental pollution and Forests Department.<ref name=\"TH20180528-1\">{{cite news | last = Rohit | first = T. K. | title = Sterlite Copper to be permanently closed, says Tamil Nadu government | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 28 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sterlite-copper-to-be-permanently-closed-says-tamil-nadu-government/article24014605.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref> The next day, Tamil Nadu's State Industries Promotion Corporation (SIPCOT) announced that it would take back 342.22 acres of land that it had given for expansion of the facility.<ref name=\"TH20180530-1\">{{cite news | title = T.N. to take back land allotted to Sterlite | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai / New Delhi | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tn-to-take-back-land-allotted-to-sterlite/article24029865.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref> Many political leaders including [[M.K.Stalin]], [[Seeman (politician)|Seeman]] and [[Anbumani Ramadoss]] criticized the sealing order, saying that it would not stand up to legal scrutiny since the government had given no reason for shutting down the factory.<ref name=\"TH20180530-2\">{{cite news | title = G.O. won't stand up to legal scrutiny: Stalin | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/go-wont-stand-up-to-legal-scrutiny-stalin/article24027956.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"TH20180530-3\">{{cite news | title = G.O. to close Sterlite plant inadequate | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/go-to-close-sterlite-plant-inadequate/article24030059.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\n=== Disappearance of S. Mugilan ===\nOn 15 February 2019, S. Mugilan, an environmental activist held a press conference in Chennai where he claimed that the senior Police officials in Tamil Nadu conspired with the officials of the Sterlite copper to carry out the gun shooting which killed 13 people, during the meeting he also voiced his fear that \"his life is in danger\" after releasing the video evidence. He also went missing on the same day in a train while travelling from Chennai to Madurai. A week ago, he released the video titled \u2018''Sterlite: Hidden Truth''\u2019 where he accused two senior police officers and the Officials of the Sterlite for plotting the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/environmental-activist-missing-thoothukudi-massacre-police|title=Activist Goes Missing Hours After Incriminating Top Cops in Thoothukudi Massacre|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> The two police officers he named were of north-Indian origin and were transferred out of the area by June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amnesty.org.in/news-update/tamil-nadu-activist-who-accused-police-of-human-rights-violations-goes-missing/|title=Tamil Nadu Activist Who Accused Police Of Human Rights Violations Goes Missing {{!}} Amnesty India|website=Amnesty International India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> The ''[[Amnesty International India]]'' reported that Mugilan had a history of fighting against sand mining mafias and polluting factories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/929706/environmental-activist-s-mugilan-who-went-missing-in-february-found-in-andhra-pradesh|title=Environmental activist S Mugilan who went missing in February found in Andhra Pradesh|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> After 100 days after his disappearance his wife alleged of constant harassment by the [[Criminal Investigation Department (India)|CB-CID]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2019/05/26034416/1139613/100-days-after-Mugilan-went-missing-wife-alleges-harassment-.vpf|title=100 days after Mugilan went missing, wife alleges harassment by CB-CID|last=|first=|date=2019-05-26|website=dtNext.in|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On July 2019, Mugilan was found after missing for 5 months in a railway station at [[Tirupati|Tirupathi]] where he was arrested by the police and handed over to the CB-CID.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/chennai/tamil-nadu-missing-activist-mugilan-traced-in-tirupati-cb-cid-begins-probe-5819602/|title=Tamil Nadu: Activist missing for five months found in Tirupati, handed over to CID|date=2019-07-07|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nOn October 28, 2018, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board reported that the sulphur-dioxide levels in the air had reduced significantly after the Sterlite plant's closure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/so2-levels-have-reduced-significantly-after-closure-of-sterlite-plant-tnpcb/article25353938.ece|title=SO2 levels have reduced significantly after closure of Sterlite plant: TNPCB|last=Simhan|first=TE Raja|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2019, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board reported that the [[Ambient air quality criteria|ambient air quality]] had improved dramatically after the closure of the plant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/tuticorin-air-quality-aqi-sterlite-copper-smelting-pollution-sipcot-tnpcb|title=Tuticorin Air Quality Improves Noticeably After Sterlite Closure: TNPCB Data|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Manjolai Riots]]\n* [[2018 Tamil Nadu protests for Kaveri water sharing]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Pollution in India]]\n[[Category:Police brutality in India]]\n[[Category:2018 in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2018 murders in Asia]]\n[[Category:May 2018 crimes in Asia|Thoothukudi_firing]]\n[[Category:Thoothukudi]]\n[[Category:Protests in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Thoothukudi police firing|2=Talk:Thoothukudi massacre#Requested move 14 April 2020 }}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = Thoothukudi Massacare\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| map         = {{Location map|Tamil Nadu|lat=8.48|long=78.04|caption=}}\n| map_caption = Location of Thoothukudi in Tamil Nadu\n| location    = [[Thoothukudi]], Tamil Nadu, [[India]]\n| target      = Protestors against [[Sterlite Copper]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|8.784117|78.099142|display=inline,title}}\n| date        = 22 May 2018\n| time        = \n| timezone    = UTC +5:30\n| type        = [[Shooting]]<!-- Don't change without valid reference -->\n| fatalities  = 13<!-- Don't change without valid reference --><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india-sterlite-protest-live-updates-tuticorin-thoothukudi-death-toll-vedanta-copper-plant-443641 |title=Anti-Sterlite protests: 15 dead, 102 injured in Thoothukudi; electricity supply to Sterlite Industries cut off}}</ref>\n| injuries    = 102<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india-sterlite-protest-live-updates-tuticorin-thoothukudi-death-toll-vedanta-copper-plant-443641 |title=Anti-Sterlite protests: 13 dead, 102 injured in Thoothukudi; electricity supply to Sterlite Industries cut off}}</ref>\n| perps       = [[Tamil Nadu Police]] & Paramilitary forces\n| weapons     = [[L1A1 SLR]] [[battle rifle]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikatan.com/news/tamilnadu/125778-this-is-the-type-of-rifle-used-in-tuticorin.html |title=\u0ba4\u0bc2\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd 11 \u0baa\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b89\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8 \u0b95\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0ba4\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf \u0b87\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0bcd}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/massacre-thoothukudi-intelligence-failure-or-deliberate-assault-81865 |title=The police firing in Thoothukudi: Intelligence failure or deliberate assault?}}</ref>\n| numparts    =\n}}\n[[File:Sterlitejpg.jpg|thumb|Protesters in large numbers take out a march against the Sterlite copper plant on May 22, 2018.]]\n\nThe '''Thoothukudi Massacre''' (also known as the '''Thoothukudi police firing''' or '''Sterlite protest firing''') is used to denote the events that took place on 22, and 23 May 2018 in [[Thoothukudi]] town of [[Tamilnadu]]. It took place during an ongoing protest against proposed expansion of copper smelter plant run by Sterlite Corporation in Thoothukudi town, ended in death of 13 persons and injuries to many, including police personnel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-44207343}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/victims-with-bleeding-injuries-and-gunshot-wounds-at-thoothukudi-gh/article23962412.ece}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-4-dead-in-police-firing-during-anti-sterlite-protest-in-tamil-nadu-s-thoothukudi-2617688}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/several-anti-sterlite-protesters-policemen-injured-in-thoothukudi/article23957774.ece}}</ref> On 22 May morning, the 100th day Anti Sterlite Protests, thousands of people marched towards the Thoothukudi Collectorate, against legal prohibitory orders passed by the district administration.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/jul/16/anti-sterlite-protests-imposition-of-sec-144-was-not-known-to-public-in-thoothukudi-reveals-report-1843883.html}}</ref> The agitated protestors overpowered police, started pelting stones and torched vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/anti-sterlite-stir-13-dead-public-property-worth-rs-10-2-million-damaged-118052500138_1.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://in.reuters.com/article/vedanta-smelter-insight/no-warning-witnesses-describe-how-police-shot-and-killed-smelter-protesters-in-thoothukudi-idINKCN1IU1W9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/victims-with-bleeding-injuries-and-gunshot-wounds-at-thoothukudi-gh/article23962412.ece}}</ref> Police opened fire killing 12 persons on 22 May, at various places in Thoothukudi Town and as the protest continued, one more person was shot dead on 23rd May.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/anti-sterlite-stir-13-dead-public-property-worth-rs-10-2-million-damaged-118052500138_1.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/one-more-dies-in-police-firing-as-tuticorin-burns-for-the-second-day-death-toll-rises-to-12-1757769.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/one-more-killed-in-fresh-firing-in-thoothukudi/article23967970.ece}}</ref> In a related incident, a women was killed when miscreants, during anti sterlite protests torched a bus on 25 May at [[Srivaikuntam]]  taking the total death toll to 14 in violent incidents related to Anti Sterlite Protests in the district.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/madurai/bus-torching-case-injured-woman-dies-in-hospital/articleshow/64421319.cms}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/arrest-anti-sterlite-protesters-who-set-bus-on-fire-thoothukudi/article24080888.ece}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nSterlite Copper has been facing resistance from the local fishermen\u2019s groups in the area ever since the plant was given permission to be established by the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board in 1994.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sudhakar|first=P.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/for-sterlite-its-crisis-situation-once-again/article4564893.ece|title=For Sterlite, it's crisis situation once again|date=2013-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Sporadic protests have occurred in [[Thoothukudi]] since 1999, directed against the Sterlite Copper smelting works, the factory owned by [[Vedanta Limited]], a subsidiary of [[Vedanta Resources]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/variety/sterlite-protests-sulphur-dioxide-vedanta-tamil-nadu/story/1/23101.html|title=Why hundreds of Tamils won't quit protests against Vedanta's Sterlite|website=www.dailyo.in|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> Protesters opposed the soil, water and air contamination caused by the factory.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/sterlite-s-pollution-problem-113041801267_1.html|title=Sterlite's pollution problem|date=2013-04-18|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Pollution studies ===\nAn epidemiological study carried out by [[Tirunelveli Medical College]] in 2006\u201307 found an increased prevalence of respiratory diseases and ear, nose and throat (ENT) morbidity in the 5-km radius of Sterlite Industries. The study reported the prevalence of respiratory diseases in the area at 13.9% which was far higher than the state average. The prevalence of asthmatic bronchitis is 2.8%, which more than two-times the state average of 1.29%. Myalgia (general body pain) is another extensively reported symptom and women were often found to have menstrual disorders, like [[Menorrhagia|menorrhagiae]] and dysmenorrhagiae in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-how-copper-plant-impacts-health-thoothukudi-people-78772|title=Sterlite - here's the proof: How the copper plant impacts health of Thoothukudi people|last=Jayaraman|first=Nityanand|date=April 1, 2018|website=thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Their report blamed it on the air pollution caused by the industry's thermal power plants and automobiles in the area.<ref>{{cite book | last = Elango  | first = S. | title = Health status and Epidemiological study around 5&nbsp;km radius of Sterlite Industries (India) Limited, Thoothukudi | publisher = Tirunelveli Medical College | date = Oct 2008 | location = Tirunelveli | pages = 106 | language = English | url = https://poromboke.files.wordpress.com/2018/03/health-report-sterlite_edited.pdf}}</ref> The [[groundwater]] iron content in the area of the plant has been found to be 17\u201320 times the allowable limit, causing additional health problems for the population already experiencing higher than average incidence of respiratory diseases. During the time of this Study at 2007, Sterlite was operating at about 18 to 42 percent, compared to its 4 Lakh Tonnes per Annum in the year 2017-2018.<ref name=\"newsminute\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-how-copper-plant-impacts-health-thoothukudi-people-78772|title=Sterlite \u2013 here's the proof: How the copper plant impacts health of Thoothukudi people|date=2018-04-01|work=The News Minute|access-date=2018-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/jul/29/sterlite-keen-to-expand-operation-in-thoothukudi-1850064.html|title=Sterlite keen to expand operation in Thoothukudi|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> \n\nThe 1998 report by [[National Environmental Engineering Research Institute]] (NEERI), the levels of selenium, arsenic and lead in treated effluent were higher than specified standards. The team also found dead birds after they consumed the water mixed with the effluent and also reported that the industry's process of cooling the effluents can cause health hazards to the staff and residents in the local region. In another instance, the NEERI reported water samples from dugwells and borewells around the spot were found to be non-[[Drinking water|drinkable]] due to its high chemical content. During 1998, the industry was operating at 10% capacity, compared to that of 2018.  <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/sterlite-here-s-proof-data-how-smelter-likely-cause-water-pollution-79055|title=Sterlite \u2013 here's proof: The data on how the smelter is likely cause for water pollution|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/news/environment/neeri-made-way-for-sterlite-to-pollute-tuticorin-60647|title=NEERI made way for Sterlite to pollute Tuticorin|last=|first=|date=|website=downtoearth.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2005 environmental audit by NEERI, the samples from a village 2-km northwest of the factory had levels of cadmium, copper, lead, chromium, and arsenic 2 to 9 times higher than allowed levels. Soil Samples were also analyzed in areas surrounding the plant during the study and [[Arsenic poisoning|arsenic]] levels ranged from 133 mg/kg to 287 mg/kg, where soils containing more than 50 mg/kg of arsenic are supposed to treated as a 'hazardous wastes' under the Indian Law.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn October 2010, Sampling tests by an NGO, Community Environmental Monitoring, found salinity level in an open well to be of 7854 mg/litre while levels exceeding 2000 mg/litre can badly damage the crops. Another water sample from a bore-well had [[sulfate]] levels 10 times higher than the average. A soil sample from the same spot contained 335 g/kg of iron and a ingestion of just 3.5 grams by a child can be a serious case of [[Iron poisoning|Iron Poisoning]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nA Scientific study in 2017, found most of the ground water samples in the area are highly contaminated with heavy metals like arsenic, lead, boron etc. which were higher than the [[World Health Organization]]'s prescribed limit.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Selvam|first=S.|last2=Antony Ravindran|first2=A.|last3=Venkatramanan|first3=S.|last4=Singaraja|first4=C.|date=2017-05-01|title=Assessment of heavy metal and bacterial pollution in coastal aquifers from SIPCOT industrial zones, Gulf of Mannar, South Coast of Tamil Nadu, India|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s13201-015-0301-3|journal=Applied Water Science|language=en|volume=7|issue=2|pages=897\u2013913|doi=10.1007/s13201-015-0301-3|issn=2190-5495}}</ref>\n\nThe Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board (TNPCB) observed that the unit has been releasing poisonous gas in the air. TNPCB identified that the sulphur dioxide levels went off the scale on the night of March 23, 2013. It showed a reading of 2939.55-mg/cubic meter against the decreed limit of 1250 mg/cubic meter.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2018/columnists/sterlite-protests-reach-a-climax.html|title=Sterlite protests reach a climax|last=Pioneer|first=The|website=The Pioneer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2018, the TNPCB accused the Sterlite Copper of causing groundwater pollution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/news/governance/sterlite-typifies-all-that-s-wrong-with-environmental-governance-in-india-60877|title=Sterlite typifies all that's wrong with environmental governance in India|website=www.downtoearth.org.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Gas leaks ===\nOn July 7th 1997, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board told the company to shut down after a sulphur dioxide gas leak which hospitalized more than 90 people.<ref>{{Cite news|last=BSCAL|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/sterlite-told-to-shut-plant-following-gas-leak-197070701041_1.html|title=Sterlite Told To Shut Plant Following Gas Leak|date=1997-07-07|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe Sterlite Copper factory also made headlines in 2013 after a suspected sulphur dioxide gas leak from one of its smelter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sterlite-plant-idINDEE93005C20130401|title=Sterlite ordered to shut large copper smelter over 'gas leak'|date=2013-04-01|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en}}</ref> The plant was blamed for health issues observed in the area related to gas leakage and residents near-by complained of coughing, [[wheezing]], eye iritation, and [[Miscarriage|miscarriages]] following the leak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1287476/sterlite-coppers-20-years-in-thoothukudi-have-been-marked-by-deaths-miscarriages-and-endless-protests/|title=Protests, miscarriages, deaths: Sterlite Copper's 20 years in Thoothukudi|last=Thomas|first=Sushma U. N, Maria|website=Quartz India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Following the alleged gas leak in March 2013, the then chief minister, the late [[J. Jayalalithaa]], ordered its closure. The company appealed to the [[National Green Tribunal Act|National Green Tribunal]], which overturned the government order. The state moved the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] against it, where the petition was still pending. The plant closed on March 27 of 2018, with the company citing a 15-day maintenance process.<ref name=\"financialexpress\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/sterlite-protest-in-tuticorin-9-killed-in-tamil-nadu-top-developments-history-reasons-behind-violence/1177652/|title=Reasons behind Killings|last=|first=|date=|work=The Financial Express|access-date=}}</ref> The Supreme Court ordered the company to pay a 100-crore fine for polluting the water, air and soil around the plant and the factory was temporarily shutdown by the pollution regulator.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sc-slaps-rs-100-cr-penalty-on-sterlite-for-pollution/article4572805.ece|title=SC slaps Rs. 100 cr. penalty on Sterlite for pollution|last=Venkatesan|first=J.|date=2013-04-02|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-05-28|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> About 150 people were arrested in protests against the plant.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn June 2019, the Tamil Nadu government reported that there were 84 incidents of gas leaks at Sterlite Copper in the year 2013 alone, to the [[Madras High Court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/84-gas-leaks-at-sterlite-in-2013-alone-tn-tells-madras-hc/articleshow/69881981.cms|title=84 gas leaks at Sterlite in 2013 alone, Tamil Nadu tells Madras HC {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Jun 21|first=TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=11:52}}</ref>\n\n== Protests ==\nAlthough there were protests were ongoing since the functioning of the plant, according to most reports the protests that lead to incidents of May 22 and May 23 started on February 11 or 12, 2018. On March 24 of thousands of protesters gathered in Thoothukudi town to demand closure of the plant, which was supported by the traders of the town by shutting down the shops. Media reports suggests that this was comparable to the [[2017 pro-jallikattu protests]]  and Thoothukudi protest has shaken the state<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2018/03/26/stir-sterlite-thoothukudi-vedanta-kamal-vivek-support.html|title=Stir against Sterlite plant sees surge in support; Kamal pledges backing|website=The Week|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>. The Sterlite management responded by stating that they have got necessary permission for expansion of the plant. Actor turned politician [[Kamal Haasan]] visited visited Kumarareddiapuram village in support of the protest on April 1.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/kamal-haasan-supports-anti-sterlite-protest/article23407062.ece|title=Kamal Haasan supports anti-Sterlite protest|date=2018-04-01|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-22|others=PTI|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Meanwhile the plant was shut for 15 days for taking up maintenance works on March 29.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2018/04/01/kamal-haasan-in-thoothukudi-in-support-of-anti-sterlite-protests.html|title=Kamal Haasan in Thoothukudi in support of anti-Sterlite protests|website=The Week|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The protesters claimed that the company went on to expand despite the rejection by the government.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Radhakrishnan|first=Sruthi|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/the-hindu-explains-sterlite-protests/article23969542.ece|title=The Hindu explains: Sterlite protests|date=2018-05-23|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vikatan.com/social-affairs/environment/120896-after-kumarettiyapuram-pandarampatti-village-people-joins-sterlite-protest-in-thoothukudi|title=\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bc6\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbe\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc8\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0bb8\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b9f\u0bcd \u0b86\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b8e\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0b9f \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bc1 \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bae\u0bcd!|last=|first=|date=|website=vikatan.com|language=ta|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/may/27/anti-sterlite-in-thoothukudi-heart-of-darkness-1819970.html|title=Anti-Sterlite in Thoothukudi: Heart of darkness|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The protests were joined by traders of Thoothukudi city central trade association on the same day following calls for a [[bandh]] by coordinator of the protest M Krishnamoorthi. It is also reported that section of the traders and lorry owners association did not participate in the March 24 protest. According to media reports police sources confirmed the compny's allegation that 'external forces' instigating agitations. One of the company representative D. Dhanavel rubbished the agitation as \u201cfalse propaganda\u201d and said the smelting plant maintained \u201cvery low\u201d emission level. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/200318/thoothukudi-foreign-hand-behind-anti-sterlite-stir.html|title=Thoothukudi: \u2018Foreign hand\u2019 behind anti-Sterlite stir|date=2018-03-20|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> [[Vaiko]] has sought an injunction against the functioning and extension of the copper smelting plant, in the Madurai Bench of High Court of Madras. A division bench of he the Court sought a counter be filed for the existing unit and posted the case for further hearing on June 7. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Reporter|first=Staff|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/puducherry/vaiko-seeks-closure-of-sterlite-copper-plant/article23688489.ece|title=Vaiko seeks closure of Sterlite copper plant|date=2018-04-27|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> \nMeanwhile, Sterlite  moved the Madras High Court for passing prohibitory orders under IPC section 144, as it feared the protest to be organised on May 22 may turn violent. The petitioner alleged that there was a plan to unleash violence and even \"burn down the factory\", and said the regulatory order banning assembly of four or more persons could prevent such incidents.   <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/sterlite-moves-hc-for-addl-security-in-view-of-may-22-protest/1309916 |work=Sterlite petitions High Court}}</ref>\nThe District Administration called up 23 people belonging to the trader associations and anti-sterlite activists from the protesters including the environmental activist Fatima Babu on 20th May for a peace meeting. The members agreed to shift the venue after pressure from the government, from the [[district collector|Collector's Office]] to SAV ground and to convert the protest as \u2018attention seeking protest\u2019. Fatima was soon expelled by the protesting group after she agreed to the shift.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/tuticorin-protests-sterlite-industries-illegally-obtained-environmental-clearance-activist-fatima-babu-tells-madras-high-court-4480681.html|title=Tuticorin protests: Sterlite Industries 'illegally obtained' environmental clearance, activist Fatima Babu tells Madras High Court|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nTwo groups of people protested separately on 22nd May. One of them was protesting a attention-seeking protest at SAV ground  and the other was marching towards the Collector's office. Soon both the groups joined together and marched toward the Collector's office. Police resorted to [[lathi charge]] and fired tear gas shells at the crowd after disagreeing with the protesters who wanted to stage a sit-in.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Joseph|first=J. Praveen Paul|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/several-anti-sterlite-protesters-policemen-injured-in-thoothukudi/article23957774.ece|title=10 killed in police firing as anti-Sterlite rally turns violent in Thoothukudi|date=2018-05-22|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> There were about 2000 police personnel and a crowd of over 20,000 protesters. The district administration played down the intelligence reports of mass mobilization of over 18,000 people in the district, assuming that expulsion of Fatima and imposition of Section 144 would de-escalate the protest.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAn employee of the Sterlite Copper claimed the involvement of groups like Makkal Athikaram and Foil Vedanta in the protests.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/880329/view-from-the-other-side-sterlite-workers-attacked-by-thoothukudi-protestors-recall-the-terror|title=View from the other side: Sterlite workers attacked by Thoothukudi protestors recall the terror|last=Govindarajan|first=Vinita|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Firing==\n\nOn May 22, 2018, thousands of people began to march to the District Dollector's office to submit a petition when the \"[[section 144]]\" was imposed. Section 144 makes a gathering of more than four people unlawful but an unofficial release said 20,000 people took out a procession towards the district-collector's office and the copper plant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2018/05/27/sterlite-protest-section-144-lifted-in-thoothukudi.html|title=Sterlite protest: Section 144 lifted in Thoothukudi|website=The Week|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Protestors were successful in entering the premises of the collectorate. The police started shooting against the protesters, \"without any formal warning\" after tear gas and lathi charge proved ineffective.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/anti-sterlite-protests-tuticorin-villagers-accuse-left-outfit-of-inciting-violence-5247129/|title=Anti-Sterlite protests: Tuticorin villagers accuse Left outfit of inciting violence|date=2018-07-06|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/6-km-stir-ended-bloodshed-671436.html|title=A 6-km stir that ended in bloodshed|date=2018-05-23|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\nThe police started shooting at the protesters and were also accused of shooting without any formal warning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/6-km-stir-ended-bloodshed-671436.html|title=A 6-km stir that ended in bloodshed|date=2018-05-23|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref> Police were also reported of intentionally shooting at the heads of the protesters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/police-targeted-protesters-shot-head-victims-families-671547.html|title=Police targeted the protesters; shot at head|date=2018-05-24|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref> 13 protesters were killed including a 17-year old school student, and dozens were injured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/she-wanted-be-lawyer-her-dreams-lie-box-thoothukudi-teen-victim-s-kin-81854|title=She wanted to be a lawyer, her dreams lie in a box|date=2018-05-24|access-date=2018-05-24|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"fivedays\" /><ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/as-tuticorin-weeps-for-13-felled-in-police-firing-a-quite-rage-persists/articleshow/64334132.cms</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/tamil-nadu/tamil-nadu-police-fired-from-assault-rifles-on-anti-sterlite-protesters-heard-saying-at-least-one-should-die-2110643.html|title=Tamil Nadu Police fired from assault rifles on anti-Sterlite protesters, heard saying at least one should die{{!}} Zee News India|website=zeenews.india.com|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref>\n\n[[First information report|FIR]]<nowiki/>s filed in local police stations, claimed that the order to shoot was issued by officers in the rank of deputy Tehsildars and people pointed out that only collectors have the authority to issue shooting orders.<ref name=\"TH20180529-1\">{{cite news | last = Pon Vasanth | first = B. A | title = Three officers in the rank of deputy tahsildar issued firing orders in Thoothukudi, say FIRs | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Madurai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 29 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/3-deputy-tahsildars-issued-firing-orders-say-firs/article24017934.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Tamil Nadu government ordered a shutdown of Internet in the entire districts of Tuticorin, Tirunelveli and Kanyakumari for five days after the firing.<ref name=\"fivedays\">{{cite web |title=Sterlite protest: Tamil Nadu orders internet suspension for five days in three southern districts |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/may/23/sterlite-protest-tamil-nadu-orders-internet-suspension-for-five-days-in-three-southern-districts-1818574.html |website=New Indian Express |accessdate=9 July 2018 |date=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n==Reactions==\n\n* [[Thirumurugan Gandhi]], the coordinator of [[May 17 Movement]], took the issue to the 38th session of the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]], Geneva in July 2018. On 9 August 2018, Thirumurugan Gandhi was detained by immigration authorities at Bangalore Airport on his return to India and charged under Section 124 A (sedition), 153 A (1) and 153 (b) of IPC for speaking about the Thoothukudi firings at the UNHRC. Court, later, refused to remand him under judicial custody as it found the charges are baseless.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/court-refuses-detain-activist-thirumurugan-gandhi-86351|title=Court refuses to detain activist Thirumurugan Gandhi|date=2018-08-10|work=The News Minute|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/aug/10/thirumurugan-gandhi-held-in-bengaluru-for-un-speech-on-police-firing-in-thoothukudi-1855732.html|title=Thirumurugan Gandhi held in Bengaluru for UN speech on police firing in Thoothukudi|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n* [[Indian National Congress]] party president [[Rahul Gandhi]] described it as \"[[state-sponsored terrorism]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://zeenews.india.com/india/anti-sterlite-protest-gunning-down-9-people-by-police-in-tamil-nadu-is-state-sponsored-terrorism-says-rahul-gandhi-2110523.html?src=fb|title=Anti-Sterlite protest: Gunning down 9 people by police in Tamil Nadu is state-sponsored terrorism, says Rahul Gandhi|date=2018-05-22|work=Zee News|access-date=2018-05-22|language=en}}</ref> \n*[[Seeman (politician)|Seeman]] condemned the firing, and his political party held a rally in Tirunelveli condemning the shooting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tamil.oneindia.com/news/tamilnadu/seeman-condemns-the-gun-firing-at-thoothukudi-protest/articlecontent-pf308746-320470.html|title=Naam Thamizhar Katchi leader Seeman condemns gun firing at Thoothukudi|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref>\n* [[Kamal Haasan]] was one of the first political leaders to arrive to Tuticorin to see the injured in the hospital, after the shootings.\n* [[Vaiko]] and [[M.K.Stalin]] demanded investigations into the shootings.<ref>http://indianexpress.com/article/india/mass-murder-of-innocent-people-dmks-stalin-questions-order-to-fire-at-anti-sterlite-protesters-5187874/</ref>\n* [[National Human Rights Commission of India]] demanded investigation into the killings.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/05/indian-police-accused-killing-11-protesters-180523134721427.html |title=Indian police accused of killing at least 11 protesters}}</ref> It asked its Director General (Investigation) to send a team headed by an [[Superintendent of Police|SP]] to visit the spot and conduct an inquiry.<ref name=\"TH20180530-1\" />\n* Tamils and [[Tamil diaspora]] across the world including [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[Europe]], [[Malaysia]], [[Sri Lanka]] and [[Australia]] held protests against the killing.\n* In support of the protests The UK's Opposition, Labour Party, has called for Vedanta to be delisted from the London Stock Exchange. [[John McDonnell]], the UK's Shadow Chancellor, said removing Vedanta Resources from the London financial markets would prevent reputational damage from the \"rogue\" company which has been operating \"illegal\" mining concerns for years. \"After the firing on the protestors this week, regulators must now take action. Vedanta must be immediately delisted from the London Stock Exchange to remove its cloak of respectability, restore confidence in the governance of the Stock Exchange, and prevent further reputational damage to London's financial markets from this rogue corporation,\" McDonnell said in a statement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uk-opposition-wants-vedanta-delisted-from-london-stock-exchange/articleshow/64331300.cms |title=UK Opposition wants Vedanta delisted on London Stock Exchange}}</ref>\n* Actor [[Rajinikanth]] said \"The entire problem started after anti-social elements attacked police and burned down collector's office, as a result, peaceful protestors were killed. If you undertake protest for each and everything, Tamil Nadu will be turned into a cemetery\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-44313804|title=Rajinikanth: Anger after actor justifies deadly police firing|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/rajinikanth-blames-anti-social-elements-for-sterlite-protest201805302030500001/ |title=Rajinikanth blames anti-social elements for Sterlite protest}}</ref> His reaction to the firing was criticized on the social media.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-superstar-rajinikanth-apologises-for-losing-cool-at-media-interaction-2621031 |title=Superstar Rajinikanth apologises for losing cool at media interaction |access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/rajinikanth-s-speech-earns-him-negative-image-on-social-media-news-tamil-sf5jD6fcigihb.html|title=Rajinikanth's speech earns him negative image on social media?|access-date=3 June 2018}}</ref> Following his controversial statements regarding the Thoothukudi police firing, the Tamil activist groups in [[Norway]] and [[Switzerland]] banned the release of Rajinikanth's film [[Kaala (2018 film)|''Kaala'']] in Norway and Switzerland by the scheduled world wide release date as of 7 June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tamil.news18.com/news/entertainment/after-norway-kaala-ban-in-swiss-too-24491.html|title=\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe \u0baa\u0b9f\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc8 \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0b9f \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u2013 News18 Tamil|website=News18 Tamil|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tamil.samayam.com/tamil-cinema/movie-news/rajinikanth-kaala-movie-banned-in-switzerland-and-norway/articleshow/64428551.cms|title=\u0bb0\u0b9c\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b92\u0bb0\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7, \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bcd \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe \u0baa\u0b9f\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8 - Samayam Tamil|date=2018-06-02|work=[[Samayam Tamil]]|access-date=2018-06-03|language=ta}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/foreign-nations-ban-rajinis-kaala-tamil-news-214931|title=Foreign nations ban Rajini's 'Kaala'? - Tamil Movie News \u2013 IndiaGlitz.com|work=IndiaGlitz.com|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref> The Tamil diaspora groups in Norway and Switzerland announced that they would not release the films of actors in the future who deliberately hurt the feelings and attitudes of Tamil people following the comments from Rajinikanth on Tamils.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tamilnews.com/2018/06/01/switzerland-ban-super-star-movie-following-norway/|title=\u0ba8\u0bcb\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7\u0baf\u0bc8 \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd '\u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bbe' \u0ba4\u0b9f\u0bc8??|last=S|first=Ashwiniya|date=2018-06-01|work=TAMIL NEWS|access-date=2018-06-03|language=en-US}}</ref> However, the ban was later lifted and the film was released within a week, a day before the scheduled worldwide release in Switzerland and Norway.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.topkino.ch/pdf/Programm24.pdf|title=Wochenprogramm|date=2018-06-11|work=Top Kino|access-date=2018-06-19|language=de-CH|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619085834/http://www.topkino.ch/pdf/Programm24.pdf|archivedate=2018-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.filmweb.no/film/article1361077.ece|title=Kaala (Tamil)|date=2018-06-01|work=Filmweb|access-date=2018-06-19|language=no-NO|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619090401/https://www.filmweb.no/film/article1361077.ece|archivedate=2018-06-19}}</ref>The actor was also summoned to appear before the one man commission probing the incident on 25th February. However, the actor cited professional engagements and disturbance caused to the public if a star of his stature arrives at the court to decline appearing before the commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/thoothukudi-sterlite-copper-plant-probe-rajinikanth-gets-exemption-from-appearance-808094.html|title=Thoothukudi Sterlite Copper plant probe: Rajinikanth gets exemption from appearance|date=2020-02-25|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nOn 28 May 2018, the Sterlite factory was sealed after an order given by the Tamil Nadu Environmental pollution and Forests Department.<ref name=\"TH20180528-1\">{{cite news | last = Rohit | first = T. K. | title = Sterlite Copper to be permanently closed, says Tamil Nadu government | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 28 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sterlite-copper-to-be-permanently-closed-says-tamil-nadu-government/article24014605.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref> The next day, Tamil Nadu's State Industries Promotion Corporation (SIPCOT) announced that it would take back 342.22 acres of land that it had given for expansion of the facility.<ref name=\"TH20180530-1\">{{cite news | title = T.N. to take back land allotted to Sterlite | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai / New Delhi | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tn-to-take-back-land-allotted-to-sterlite/article24029865.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref> Many political leaders including [[M.K.Stalin]], [[Seeman (politician)|Seeman]] and [[Anbumani Ramadoss]] criticized the sealing order, saying that it would not stand up to legal scrutiny since the government had given no reason for shutting down the factory.<ref name=\"TH20180530-2\">{{cite news | title = G.O. won't stand up to legal scrutiny: Stalin | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/go-wont-stand-up-to-legal-scrutiny-stalin/article24027956.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"TH20180530-3\">{{cite news | title = G.O. to close Sterlite plant inadequate | newspaper = The Hindu | location = Chennai | language = English | publisher = The Hindu Group | date = 30 May 2018 | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/go-to-close-sterlite-plant-inadequate/article24030059.ece | access-date = 30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\n=== Disappearance of S. Mugilan ===\nOn 15 February 2019, S. Mugilan, an environmental activist held a press conference in Chennai where he claimed that the senior Police officials in Tamil Nadu conspired with the officials of the Sterlite copper to carry out the gun shooting which killed 13 people, during the meeting he also voiced his fear that \"his life is in danger\" after releasing the video evidence. He also went missing on the same day in a train while travelling from Chennai to Madurai. A week ago, he released the video titled \u2018''Sterlite: Hidden Truth''\u2019 where he accused two senior police officers and the Officials of the Sterlite for plotting the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/environmental-activist-missing-thoothukudi-massacre-police|title=Activist Goes Missing Hours After Incriminating Top Cops in Thoothukudi Massacre|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> The two police officers he named were of north-Indian origin and were transferred out of the area by June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amnesty.org.in/news-update/tamil-nadu-activist-who-accused-police-of-human-rights-violations-goes-missing/|title=Tamil Nadu Activist Who Accused Police Of Human Rights Violations Goes Missing {{!}} Amnesty India|website=Amnesty International India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> The ''[[Amnesty International India]]'' reported that Mugilan had a history of fighting against sand mining mafias and polluting factories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/929706/environmental-activist-s-mugilan-who-went-missing-in-february-found-in-andhra-pradesh|title=Environmental activist S Mugilan who went missing in February found in Andhra Pradesh|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> After 100 days after his disappearance his wife alleged of constant harassment by the [[Criminal Investigation Department (India)|CB-CID]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2019/05/26034416/1139613/100-days-after-Mugilan-went-missing-wife-alleges-harassment-.vpf|title=100 days after Mugilan went missing, wife alleges harassment by CB-CID|last=|first=|date=2019-05-26|website=dtNext.in|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On July 2019, Mugilan was found after missing for 5 months in a railway station at [[Tirupati|Tirupathi]] where he was arrested by the police and handed over to the CB-CID.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/chennai/tamil-nadu-missing-activist-mugilan-traced-in-tirupati-cb-cid-begins-probe-5819602/|title=Tamil Nadu: Activist missing for five months found in Tirupati, handed over to CID|date=2019-07-07|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nOn October 28, 2018, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board reported that the sulphur-dioxide levels in the air had reduced significantly after the Sterlite plant's closure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/so2-levels-have-reduced-significantly-after-closure-of-sterlite-plant-tnpcb/article25353938.ece|title=SO2 levels have reduced significantly after closure of Sterlite plant: TNPCB|last=Simhan|first=TE Raja|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2019, the Tamil Nadu Pollution Control Board reported that the [[Ambient air quality criteria|ambient air quality]] had improved dramatically after the closure of the plant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/environment/tuticorin-air-quality-aqi-sterlite-copper-smelting-pollution-sipcot-tnpcb|title=Tuticorin Air Quality Improves Noticeably After Sterlite Closure: TNPCB Data|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Manjolai Riots]]\n* [[2018 Tamil Nadu protests for Kaveri water sharing]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Pollution in India]]\n[[Category:Police brutality in India]]\n[[Category:2018 in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2018 murders in Asia]]\n[[Category:May 2018 crimes in Asia|Thoothukudi_firing]]\n[[Category:Thoothukudi]]\n[[Category:Protests in India]]\n", "name_user": "Edits12pm", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProtests", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thoothukudi_massacre"}
